{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 01:14:56.091597", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and baseline\n- Routing domain: RIP-based, full-mesh internal FRR routers, a gateway to external FRR zones, and a WireGuard VPN overlay intended to gate access to specific external web servers (web_server_1_1, web_server_1_2).\n- General health: Network-wide L3 reachability is good. Multiple cross-zone pings show 0% loss and low RTTs (~1–3 ms). RIP adjacencies and routes are populated across internal and external routers.\n\nKey findings\n\n1) Policy breach: “VPN-only” web servers are reachable without VPN\n- Observation: From a non-VPN internal host (host_2), both ICMP and HTTP to web_server_1_1 (20.0.0.3) and web_server_1_2 (20.0.0.4) succeed.\n  - host_2 -> 20.0.0.3 curl timing: ~1.1–7.9 ms, no failures.\n  - host_2 -> 20.0.0.4 curl timing: ~1.0–2.5 ms, no failures.\n  - host_2 can ping 20.0.0.3/.4 with 0% loss.\n- Expected behavior: web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 should be accessible only via the VPN (from host_1 over the WireGuard overlay), not directly from non-VPN hosts.\n- Evidence the traffic is not using the VPN:\n  - On host_1 (the VPN client), “ip route get 20.0.0.3/4” resolves via default gateway on eth0 (10.0.0.1), not via wg0.\n  - host_2 has no wg0 interface, yet can access 20.0.0.3/4 freely.\n\n2) Route leakage of the server LAN (20.0.0.0/24) into the internal RIP domain\n- external_router_1 FRR running config:\n  - router rip\n    - network 192.168.0.0/16\n    - network 20.0.0.0/24\n- external_router_1 routing table: 20.0.0.0/24 is directly connected (br0).\n- gateway_router routing table: learns 20.0.0.0/24 via RIP (R>* 20.0.0.0/24 via 192.168.0.60, eth2).\n- Internal routers propagate this to LANs, hence internal hosts route directly to 20.0.0.3/4 without VPN.\n\n3) WireGuard overlay is up and reachable from host_1\n- vpn_server_1: UDP 51820 listening; wg show displays interface wg0 with peer 172.16.1.11/32 (host_1).\n- host_1: wg0 up at 172.16.1.11/24; wg show configured.\n- host_1 -> 172.16.1.1 (WG server side) ping succeeds (0% loss, a few ms).\n- host_2 cannot reach 172.16.1.0/24 (Destination Net Unreachable from router), consistent with it not being a VPN client and the overlay not being advertised by RIP (correct behavior).\n\n4) Minor configuration oddities that do not appear service-impacting\n- vpn_server_1 systemd status shows wg-quick@wg0 “inactive (dead)”, yet wg0 is up and passing traffic. Likely the interface was brought up outside systemd; not a functional fault.\n- gateway_router FRR config contains “network None” under router rip, but routing tables appear correct and stable.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary device: external_router_1 (FRR). It is advertising 20.0.0.0/24 into RIP (network 20.0.0.0/24), making the server LAN directly reachable from the internal domain.\n- Secondary propagation: gateway_router and internal routers correctly learn and forward the leaked route, enabling non-VPN hosts to reach the “VPN-only” servers.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfiguration of RIP on external_router_1 resulting in route leakage of the server LAN (20.0.0.0/24) into the internal network. This, combined with the absence of access-control filtering, allows non-VPN clients to reach web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 directly, violating the “accessible only via the VPN” requirement.\n\nImpact assessment\n- All internal non-VPN hosts can directly access the restricted web servers over the underlay, bypassing the intended VPN overlay controls. This is a security/policy breach rather than a connectivity outage.\n- Core IP connectivity and VPN overlay health are otherwise normal.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 23663, "output_tokens": 4665, "total_tokens": 28328, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 22656}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3648}}}
